    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nsetting the msg target to dialog, means the window will sometimes not close with `:q` and movement keys will be overridden after opening.\n\nim unsure of the goal of allowing to set the msg target to `dialog` with the current behavior.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\nrequire(\"vim._core.ui2\").enable({\n  enable = true,\n  msg = {\n    targets = {\n      default = \"msg\",\n      shell_cmd = \"dialog\",\n      shell_err = \"dialog\",\n      shell_out = \"dialog\",\n      shell_ret = \"dialog\",\n    },\n  },\n})\n```\n\nwhen running `:!ls` the dialog window will open the output but it can not be focused or closed using keybinds. instead you have to use `:fclose`. if run again or with sufficient output that the buffer is overflowing the dialog window is still unfocused but now the arrow keys will both: scroll the window and move around in the normal buffer. if you close the window with `:fclose`, your arrow up & down keys will now stop working in the editor.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\ni would expect to be able to close the window with `esc`/`q` it with `:q`.\ni would also expect movement in the editor to not affect the dialog.\nclosing the window should also not disallow my movement keys.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.13.0 commit 7662001c482d63e1119aafcebc0e13d1201a2805\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNA\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nNixOS\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nsource",
